H1> About the cache

P> The cache stores rendered fragments of your site so e107 doesn't have to rebuild them on every request. Properly tuned, it cuts MySQL load dramatically and shortens response times.

SHOT> cache/admin-cache.png | Cache status panel with the clear-cache buttons

Q> What's this section for?
A> Setting [b]Cache Status[/b] to [i]on[/i] saves certain areas of your site (menus, news lists, etc.). This reduces calls to MySQL and vastly speeds the site up.

Q> I altered the theme I'm using but the change isn't visible – is it cached?
A> Most likely yes. Switching themes clears the cache automatically, but editing `theme.php` does not. Either turn the cache off while you iterate, or click [b]Clear cache[/b] after each change.

TIP> While developing a theme or plugin, set Cache Status to [i]off[/i]. Re-enable it before going live.

Q> Can I save the cache to files on the hard drive?
A> Yes. Make sure the directory `e107_system/<sitehash>/cache/` is writable (chmod 755 / 775 on Linux), then enable file caching on this page.

WARN> If you accidentally cache a logged-in version of a page, log out and clear the cache immediately to avoid leaking session-bound content to guests.
